title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 1940 Light Rifle MK-I and MK-II "VERY RARE" 9mm Luger. Caliber
postcontent:
******************Make an offer******************
Smith & Wesson Model 1940 Light Rifle MK-II in 9mm Luger: In 1940 Smith & Wesson manufactured the Model 1940 Light Rifle for the British government. However, because Smith & Wesson designed the rifle around the 9mm Luger of American manufacture the rifles failed the British 5000 round endurance test at the Enfield Arsenal. The arsenal used 9mm Luger ammunition of European design that had a breech pressure of 7000 foot/pounds of energy, which is much higher than the American ammunition. The British government asked Smith & Wesson to make design changes to handle the more powerful European round. Smith & Wesson redesigned the rifle with an oversleeve to strengthen the frame and to serve as a bolt lock safety, negating the need for the hand operated safety lever. To distinguish between the two models, Smith & Wesson stamped the first as the Mark-I and the second model Mark-II. The Smith & Wesson manufactured 2200 frames in all with serial numbers ranging from 1 to 2200. However Smith & Wesson only sold 1227 rifles to the British & Canadian governments. At the end of WWII the British & Canadian Light Rifles were cut up and dumped into the English Channel with the exception of five rifles which are now in the Tower of London, British Military Museum and the Enfield Arsenal. In 1974 Smith & Wesson discovered crates of Model 1940 Light Rifles, and subsequently sold as C&R (curio & relics). In this batch of Light Rifles there were a total of 217, of which 137 were Mark-Is and 80 Mark-IIs. Smith & Wesson records indicate that these Light Rifles were sold on March 30, 1975 to GT Distributors, Rossville, GA.  "Please Note: The Smith & Wesson letter indicates that it is extremely important that these rifles not be loaded or fired with any of the modern 9mm ammunition. They are only sold as collector pieces and are hazardous to fire.

title: For Sale:  Buffalo Bore Ammo - .45 Super Ammo - 200 gr. J.H.P.(1,200fps/M.E.639 ft.lbs.) - 50 Round Box
postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=77

45 Super is externally/dimensionally identical to 45 acp or 45 acp+P and is designed to be used in 45 acp semi auto pistols that have been fitted with stronger than normal recoil springs and a shock buffer, plus a couple other modifications. While you can shoot 45 SUPER out of some stock 45 acp+P pistols such as the Glock 21, HK USP or the full sized all steel 1911, you will batter your pistol if you do not have them modified to handle the extra pressure and slide velocity of the 45 Super.


To learn about the modifications your 45 acp pistol needs to reliably and safely fire 45 SUPER, contact Garey Hindman at REDACTED. Garey is the foremost authority on 45 Super modifications/conversions for your 45 acp and Garey performs such conversions for a living.


The below velocities were fired from my Colt Gold Cup Govt. Model (5 inch) that was converted by Garey.

1. Item # 45S185-----------1330 fps (185gr. Jhp)
2. Item # 45S200-----------1235 fps (200gr. Jhp)
3. Item # 45S230-----------1131 fps (230gr. Jhp)
4. Item # 45S230FMJ----1133 fps (230gr. FMJ-FLAT NOSE) 
5. Item # 45S255-----------1090 fps  (HARD CAST-FLAT NOSE)

 As always with Buffalo Bore Ammunition, we use real world firearms to give you real world data and results.

All our 45 Super ammunition is loaded with flash suppressed powders so that if you have to fire in low light (when the criminal element is out) you will not be blinded by your own gun fire at the worst possible moment.


All three of the JHP loads were designed for anti-personel use and for hunting small big game like deer. The two solid bullet loads were designed for breaking large bones like a bears shoulders or skull, but will work for anti-personel use as well if you need to shoot through cover like car doors or stick frame walls.
